1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,340
 - Hello, and welcome to this lecture on the structure

2
00:00:02,340 --> 00:00:03,780
 of a Django application.

3
00:00:03,780 --> 00:00:06,580
 It's a little early to be going through all the detail,

4
00:00:06,580 --> 00:00:07,860
 and there'll be some things that we're not really

5
00:00:07,860 --> 00:00:10,660
 going to understand until a little bit later in the course.

6
00:00:10,660 --> 00:00:13,480
 But I wanted to sort of show you the lay of the land

7
00:00:13,480 --> 00:00:16,000
 so that as we add features, you realize that there's

8
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,360
 sort of a method to the madness.

9
00:00:19,360 --> 00:00:23,340
 And so, Django is a way of building web applications.

10
00:00:23,340 --> 00:00:27,560
 Django has a pattern within itself that, you know,

11
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:30,480
 organizes folders in a certain way, and puts files

12
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:34,900
 in certain places, and we're gonna build these projects

13
00:00:34,900 --> 00:00:39,040
 and applications, and you're like, why are these things

14
00:00:39,040 --> 00:00:40,560
 organized the way they are?

15
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:42,480
 Well, it has to do with the fact that if you go

16
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:45,240
 from one Django project to another Django project,

17
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:48,040
 you can, you know, fit right in and understand

18
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:49,160
 how things are going to work.

19
00:00:49,160 --> 00:00:52,460
 So, the important terminology that's, I don't know,

20
00:00:52,460 --> 00:00:55,360
 a bit frustrating is there is projects and applications,

21
00:00:55,360 --> 00:00:59,520
 and from, Django has this notion of, you have applications,

22
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:03,300
 and you might have a project, which is really basically

23
00:01:03,300 --> 00:01:06,460
 a website, and then, you know, some applications,

24
00:01:06,460 --> 00:01:08,280
 but if you had two projects, you could share

25
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:09,820
 applications between them.

26
00:01:09,820 --> 00:01:13,760
 And so, it's one or more applications per project

27
00:01:13,760 --> 00:01:17,320
 with the ability to potentially reuse application

28
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:19,380
 across multiple projects.

29
00:01:19,380 --> 00:01:22,360
 And so, we're gonna work with my DJ4E samples,

30
00:01:22,360 --> 00:01:24,160
 which I hope you have downloaded somewhere,

31
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:26,220
 at least so that you can look at the files,

32
00:01:26,220 --> 00:01:28,200
 look at the folders, look at the names of the files,

33
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:29,960
 and look at the contents of the files.

34
00:01:29,960 --> 00:01:31,940
 This will all make more sense when you get a little

35
00:01:31,940 --> 00:01:34,260
 farther down the road.

36
00:01:34,260 --> 00:01:37,340
 So, here is an LS statement, LS minus L,

37
00:01:37,340 --> 00:01:39,200
 DJ4E samples, and hello.

38
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:42,280
 This is within the folder DJ4E samples.

39
00:01:42,280 --> 00:01:45,040
 There are two basic folders.

40
00:01:45,040 --> 00:01:47,280
 One is, in effect, the project wide settings,

41
00:01:47,280 --> 00:01:51,240
 which is the same name as the folder that we're in.

42
00:01:51,240 --> 00:01:55,460
 So, it's DJ4E samples slash DJ4E samples.

43
00:01:55,460 --> 00:01:59,060
 And then, there is the first application, which is hello.

44
00:01:59,060 --> 00:02:00,460
 And there's a couple things here,

45
00:02:00,460 --> 00:02:02,760
 like the underscore underscore init dot py.

46
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:04,420
 You'll notice it's an empty file.

47
00:02:04,420 --> 00:02:07,920
 It's just some bookkeeping that helps Python know

48
00:02:07,920 --> 00:02:11,000
 that there are files that contain classes

49
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:12,100
 and objects in here.

50
00:02:12,100 --> 00:02:17,820
 Settings dot py and URLs dot py and wgsi dot py

51
00:02:17,820 --> 00:02:20,720
 is kind of like the traffic cop

52
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:23,440
 for this entire application that routes things

53
00:02:23,440 --> 00:02:26,280
 coming into the right, this entire project

54
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:28,360
 that routes things to the right application.

55
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:31,400
 And then, within the application, we have some files.

56
00:02:31,400 --> 00:02:33,560
 And you're really gonna learn a lot

57
00:02:33,560 --> 00:02:34,860
 about object-oriented programming,

58
00:02:34,860 --> 00:02:37,800
 because all these files contain objects.

59
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:40,840
 So, Django is a large piece of software,

60
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:43,480
 and you change its behavior by defining objects

61
00:02:43,480 --> 00:02:44,760
 that accomplish things, and then,

62
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:46,840
 in effect, registering those objects.

63
00:02:46,840 --> 00:02:50,040
 So, a common thing will be to take something like, you know,

64
00:02:50,040 --> 00:02:53,240
 admin dot py or models dot py, create a data model,

65
00:02:53,240 --> 00:02:55,720
 and then tell the admin user interface

66
00:02:55,720 --> 00:02:59,480
 that you didn't write how to show your model,

67
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:02,000
 and so you write stuff in admin dot py

68
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:05,960
 to communicate into the admin user interface

69
00:03:05,960 --> 00:03:09,360
 how your data model that Django currently knows nothing about

70
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:11,720
 is supposed to be shown, et cetera, et cetera.

71
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:13,300
 And so, there's a lot of files,

72
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:16,460
 and we will talk through these files.

73
00:03:16,460 --> 00:03:20,600
 Now, this is an example of a request response.

74
00:03:20,600 --> 00:03:21,760
 It's a web application.

75
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:24,600
 And so, what we'll talk about is,

76
00:03:24,600 --> 00:03:26,940
 once a request makes it into the server,

77
00:03:26,940 --> 00:03:29,020
 it's gonna do some work and then produce a response.

78
00:03:29,020 --> 00:03:31,480
 But in that, we're gonna look at all of the work

79
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:33,760
 that goes back and forth.

80
00:03:33,760 --> 00:03:36,600
 And there's effectively like a routing step

81
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,560
 where it picks what part of your application

82
00:03:38,560 --> 00:03:40,840
 to run this route this request to.

83
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:44,920
 There is a view part, which is going to receive it

84
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:47,380
 and potentially store data.

85
00:03:47,380 --> 00:03:49,640
 Some would call that the model.

86
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:51,440
 The storing of the data is certainly the model,

87
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:54,280
 but the receiving of the possibly new input data

88
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:55,780
 like you're gonna create a new thing,

89
00:03:55,780 --> 00:03:57,200
 that would be the model.

90
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:59,320
 And then the view, at some point,

91
00:03:59,320 --> 00:04:01,760
 you gotta finish it and send something back out.

92
00:04:01,760 --> 00:04:03,600
 And that's the purpose of the view.

93
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:07,080
 We call this pattern for building web applications,

94
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:08,560
 model view controller.

95
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:12,280
 And it's not like you can't build applications any other way.

96
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:14,640
 It's just by saying, it's a terminology

97
00:04:14,640 --> 00:04:17,340
 that I can say going forward, that's the model,

98
00:04:17,340 --> 00:04:19,860
 that's the view, and that's a controller function.

99
00:04:19,860 --> 00:04:22,080
 And you don't have to know it right now,

100
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:25,240
 but these are words that are, they're loaded

101
00:04:25,240 --> 00:04:27,960
 and have valuable meaning to us to be able to do.

102
00:04:27,960 --> 00:04:31,360
 So at some point in this picture on the left side,

103
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:32,840
 we have a browser.

104
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:35,620
 DOM stands for the document object model.

105
00:04:35,620 --> 00:04:38,560
 And at some point, the person clicks somewhere

106
00:04:38,560 --> 00:04:41,080
 in the current web page they're looking at.

107
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:44,760
 And the web browser intercepts that and says,

108
00:04:44,760 --> 00:04:47,080
 oh, okay, I've got your click right here.

109
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:49,100
 The web browser intercepts it

110
00:04:49,100 --> 00:04:51,620
 and then makes a socket connection across the internet,

111
00:04:51,620 --> 00:04:54,600
 which we've seen before, and then does a get request.

112
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:57,600
 And that is what then goes into the server.

113
00:04:57,600 --> 00:05:00,360
 And so the three functions are the routing,

114
00:05:00,360 --> 00:05:02,080
 the views, and the models.

115
00:05:02,080 --> 00:05:05,560
 And there is an overall configuration file,

116
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:09,320
 the settings.py, which is sort of how you just say,

117
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:11,800
 oh, here's my view files, read these view files,

118
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:13,000
 read these model files.

119
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:16,220
 So the settings.py kinda controls everything.

120
00:05:16,220 --> 00:05:20,440
 But when a request first comes in, it consults urls.py,

121
00:05:20,440 --> 00:05:25,440
 and then for the project, and then it will include urls.py

122
00:05:25,440 --> 00:05:27,520
 from each of the applications.

123
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:30,840
 So once it's chosen what view to run,

124
00:05:30,840 --> 00:05:33,760
 it looks at the URL, pulls out the pieces of the URL,

125
00:05:33,760 --> 00:05:37,080
 and finds the views in views.py.

126
00:05:37,080 --> 00:05:41,180
 That's a Python file that has the destinations

127
00:05:41,180 --> 00:05:43,360
 for these incoming URLs.

128
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:46,000
 There's a file called forms.py, which we'll see later,

129
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,820
 that is used to make the forms aspect,

130
00:05:49,820 --> 00:05:52,980
 the part that you fill in as pretty as possible.

131
00:05:52,980 --> 00:05:55,680
 And then we take the resulting data

132
00:05:55,680 --> 00:05:58,020
 that we're gonna send back and we merge that in

133
00:05:58,020 --> 00:05:59,760
 through what's called a template.

134
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:02,440
 And then if there's any data that we need stored,

135
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:06,000
 we call the model and we store that in a database.

136
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,680
 And there's this file called model.py,

137
00:06:08,680 --> 00:06:12,320
 which informs how we store data in the database.

138
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:14,200
 And then when that's all done,

139
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:17,560
 we read potentially new data from the database,

140
00:06:17,560 --> 00:06:19,080
 merge that into a template,

141
00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:22,020
 and then send a response back to the browser,

142
00:06:22,020 --> 00:06:25,560
 and then that response is all shown to the end user.

143
00:06:25,560 --> 00:06:29,880
 And so that really is the request into the server

144
00:06:29,880 --> 00:06:31,380
 through a Django application,

145
00:06:31,380 --> 00:06:33,120
 pulling data from various places,

146
00:06:33,120 --> 00:06:35,080
 merging a template back in,

147
00:06:35,080 --> 00:06:40,080
 and then sending a response back to the application.

148
00:06:40,080 --> 00:06:44,600
 So up next, we're gonna talk about virtual hosting.

149
00:06:44,600 --> 00:06:46,680
 Now, in general, you're not gonna have to worry about this.

150
00:06:46,680 --> 00:06:50,160
 It just kind of explains how something like Python Anywhere

151
00:06:50,160 --> 00:06:54,000
 is able to manage a whole lot of domains on a single system.

152
